answers.body_markdown:
One way to do this is to split the random word into characters, and then use [`array_intersect`][1] to find the matching characters between that and the set of correct letters. If the count of that array is &gt;= 3, the word has been found:

    function getWordBasedOnLetter($correctLetters, $randomWord)
    {
        $randomLetters = str_split($randomWord);
        $matchingLetters = array_intersect($correctLetters, $randomLetters);
        if (count($matchingLetters) &gt;= 3) {
            return &quot;found&quot;;
        }
        return &quot;not found&quot;;
    }

For your sample data this outputs `found`. [Demo on 3v4l.org][2]

**Update**

If you want to make the test based on the length of the random word, it is probably better to use [`array_diff`][3] as that will work better when there are duplicated letters in `$randomWord`. In this case, set the test to be the number of non-matching letters to be less than a threshold of the length of the word (e.g. 40%):

    function getWordBasedOnLetter($correctLetters, $randomWord)
    {
        $randomLetters = str_split($randomWord);
        $differentLetters = array_diff($randomLetters, $correctLetters);
        if (count($differentLetters) &lt; .4 * strlen($randomWord)) {
            return &quot;found&quot;;
        }
        return &quot;not found&quot;;
    }

[Demo on 3v4l.org][4]


  [1]: https://www.php.net/manual/en/function.array-intersect.php
  [2]: https://3v4l.org/rhGvK
  [3]: https://www.php.net/manual/en/function.array-diff.php
  [4]: https://3v4l.org/K5Rvm

