answers.body_markdown:
Yes you can, but for that matter you don&#39;t need it. You have to run your function a hundred times. Otherwise you can create a bash file and run it according to your operating system and run ‍‍`npm start` code every time. job or schedule in OS.

But the simplest way is to use a recursive function.

    import personfaces from &#39;./dist/index&#39;;
    
    const dnte = new personfaces();
    
    var count = 100
    recursiveFun(0);
    function recursiveFun(index) {
      if (index === count)
        return;
      dnte.getImage({ width: 256, height: 256, type: &#39;file&#39; })
        .then(res =&gt; {
          console.log(&#39;result-&gt;&#39;, res);
          recursiveFun(index + 1)
        })
        .catch(err =&gt; {
          console.log(&#39;error-&gt;&#39;, err);
          recursiveFun(index)
        });
    }

second way is using node module:

The [p-iteration][1] module on npm implements the Array iteration methods so they can be used in a very straightforward way with async/await.

Loop through an array to execute asynchronous actions on each element.
Sometimes you must execute an [asynchronous action on each elements of an array][2], but you must wait for the previous action to complete before proceed to the next.


  [1]: https://github.com/toniov/p-iteration
  [2]: https://www.npmjs.com/package/node-async-loop

